XIII. Having proved that the Church has received no power to frama any new doctrine, let us now spealr of the power which our opponente attribute to it in the interpretationes the Scripture. We have not the least objection to admit, that if a controversy arise respecting any doctrine, there is no better or more certain remedy than to assemble a council of trus bishops, in which the controverted doctrine may be discussed. For such a decision, formed by the common consent of the pastors of the Churohes, after an invocation of the Spirit of Christ, will have far greater weight, than if every one of them separately were to maintain it in preaching to his people, or if it were the result of a private conference between a few indivi- duals.
